column8: Description

column2: Role of Palliative Care in times of Covid-19: Dr M R Rajagopal
column8: A person’s right to be treated, not merely as a unidimensional patient suffering with a life-altering disease, but as a human being with multiple dimensions that determine her or his quality of life, lies at the heart of Dr Rajagopal’s work on Palliative Care. Dr Rajagopal believed in the need for a more holistic approach to caregiving for those who have been diagnosed as terminally ill. Pallium India, a charitable trust set up by him embraces the entire ecosystem of illness - pain, distress, discomfort, the loss of dignity - for the patient and for those who are closely connected with her or him. Dr Rajagopal’s work with the WHO Collaborating Center at Pain and Policy Studies Group (PPSG) in Madison-Wisconsin involved withdrawing regulatory barriers in availability of opioids for pain relief in India. This collaborative work resulted in the Government of India asking all its State Governments to bring in an amendment in narcotic regulations. Implementation of this needs State by State advocacy and opioid availability workshops. In recognition of the yeomen service to the field of palliative medicine, Dr Rajagopal was awarded a Padma Shree in 2018. He was also identified as one of the 30 most influential leaders in hospice and palliative medicine by the American Academy of Hospice and Palliative Medicine.

column2: Maintaining an ethical stand in clinical trials: Meena Dalal
column8: With an MSc. in clinical research, Meena Dalal started her career as Clinical Trial Assistant in 2009; pacing up to be a Sr. Centralized Monitoring Lead at IQVIA alias Quintiles. In May 2019, she founded Trial Guna, a CRO that stands to make reliable healthcare solutions available to the world. So far, Trial Guna has supported 13 Ayush submission studies (Nutraceuticals & Herbal), 04 US-FDA submission studies (Biosimilars & Oncology), 01 European submission study (Braille comprehension on the medicinal package for Visually Challenged) and is currently working on 03 COVID-19 treatment studies for global support. Dalal leads clinical trials that are compliant with regulations and maintain an ethical stand beyond scientific outcomes. Her biggest influence has been her grandfather, an archaeologist and the only educated person in her family during her formative years. Her hobbies include reading and classical music.

column2: Impact of the pandemic on animals: Dr Pavan Kumar
column8: With a vision to impacting Veterinary Healthcare Services in India, Dr. Pawan Kumar founded Cessna Lifeline Veterinary Healthcare in 2005. With a focus on diagnostics, innovation and training, Cessna is today a multi-speciality clinic with branches in multiple locations. Dr Kumar has a masters in Veterinary Sciences with a specialization in Orthopedics.

column2: Awareness is the first step to safety : Dr Jagdish Chaturvedi
column8: Dr. Jagdish Chaturvedi, popularly referred to as ‘Corona Wala Doctor’ because of his viral videos on corona virus, is a doctor and a stand-up comic – but not just that. He is also a practicing ENT surgeon, innovator of 18+ medical devices, listed in 35-Innovators-under-35 by MIT technology review, and an author of 3 published titles. His comedy is observational – inspired from real life routines – non-offensive and non-political, and thus relatable to audiences from across. He has given over 200+ performances at corporate events in India as well as an equal number of public performances across India, Australia, United Kingdom, UAE, Thailand and Singapore. His Youtube channel has 120K+ subscribers and over 13 million video views across 65+ comedy videos.

column2: Use your power responsibly: Ragini Dwivedi
column8: In her decade-long career as an actor, Ragini Dwivedi has worked in films in all four south Indian languages - Kannada, Malayalam, Tamil and Telegu. Working with top actors and directors she has elevated now to doing solo leads in women-centric films. A multi-faceted personality she is also an entrepreneur, running an events company and a chain of restaurants; an  active social worker working for causes of HIV aids, breast cancer, child labour and women empowerment; and is the face of cricket in Karnataka, not only promoting but owning teams in various leagues.

column2: Not physical distancing but social cohesion: Dr Giridhara Babu
column8: Giridhara R Babu is Professor and Head – Life Course Epidemiology at Public Health Foundation of India. After an MBBS from Kasturba medical college Manipal, and MPH and PhD from UCLA (University of California Los Angeles), he has worked for two decades in public health research, practice and academics. He began his career at the Center for Community Medicine of the AIIMS, New Delhi as a Junior Resident. Next, he worked with WHO where he led the efforts in stopping polio transmission in the state of Karnataka. He initiated advocacy for measles surveillance in Karnataka leading to constitution of Multi Year Plan (MYP) for Measles elimination in India. He is awarded the prestigious intermediate fellowship of Wellcome Trust-DBT India Alliance to start a cohort study. The cohort is named as MAASTHI (Maternal Antecedents of Adiposity Studying the Transgenerational role of Hyperglycemia and Insulin). Giridhara has over 80 papers published in national and international high impact journals. He is the Member of Epidemiology and surveillance Research group constituted by ICMR National Task Force for COVID-I9. He is also on the Technical Analysis Committee of the Government of Karnataka to tackle COVID-19. He is actively involved in writing articles for general public, providing his expert opinion to media houses and consultation to several states. His work on COVID-19 can be accessed here https://giridhar.org/covid-19/.

column2: What role can corporates play in the time of the pandemic? : Minol Ajekar
column8: Minol helms Corporate Communication and Corporate Social Responsibility (CRS), in addition to Business Process, for the Puravankara Group. Armed with a masters degree from Monash University, Melbourne, she has worked in the financial sector in Australia for a few years before her homeland called her back again. Puravankara is her first foray in real estate, where she has been instrumental in shaping the functions of the company. She refers to herself as an Equal Opportunity Offender, enjoys stories and storytellers, tries to see one new city/country every year, makes times for music and film festivals and will try almost any food at least once.

column2: How can Indian governance step up in the time of the pandemic? : Simar Suri
column8: The head of the International Practice Group at Suri & Company Law Firm, in her decade long experience as a practicing lawyer, Simar Suri has been engaged in several matters closely connected to effective global governance. In addition to this, she established established the Social Welfare and Public Policy practice within the Law Firm.She has spearheaded several legal programs targeting improved public health from tobacco control. As the youngest associate member and sole lawyer on the Independent Commission on Development and Health, she has advised cabinet-level policymakers on issues that have a direct impact on all the primary stakeholders. She also has first-hand knowledge of how global connections can benefit policy and governance, selected to represent India at the East Asia Future Leaders Programme in Japan under the aegis of the Japan–East Asia Network of Exchange for Students and Youth (JENESYS) Programme in 2010.She is currently working closely with the COVID Consultative Group set up under the guidance of the Hon’ble Chief Minister of Karnataka and Dr. Vishal Rao as an advisor for legal and government affairs. Suri graduated from the London School of Economics and Political Science, UK, after after completing an honours degree in Philosophy from St. Stephens College, Delhi University.

column2: International trade relations in the face of the pandemic: Gitesh Agarwal
column8: Gitesh Agarwal is currently the Trade and Investment Commissioner for Queensland and a strategic idea consultant, with over 20 years of experience from different industries and functions, spanning from sales, marketing, international alliances, B2B, B2G, business development, P&L and SBU management, CEO, and CMO. With an MBA in International Business, not only was he able to advise more than 2,000 companies with macro market entry strategies across multiple sectors, but is also experienced in identifying niches in markets and analysing them to develop customised strategies. As a certified trainer-facilitator in leadership and soft skills, he knows how to create and manage dynamic relationships with all stakeholders and has been recognized for his high professional merit and excellence in his entire career.

column2: Challenges of the health workers in a pandemic : Dr. Vijay Raju Krupesh
column8: With an MBBS and a post-graduate in anaesthesia, Dr Krupesh has been practicing intensive care since 2003. He holds a Fellowship in Critical care as well as a European Diploma in Critical Care, and currently serves as the Lead Consultant in Intensive care HCG, Bangalore.

column2: Innovating for Covid-19: Vaibhav Chhabra and Nitesh Jangir
column8: Vaibhav Chhabra is a mechanical engineer by education but a carpenter by passion. A graduate from Boston University, Vaibhav spent the first 2 years of his career at EyeNetra, a startup from MIT Media Labs, building portable Virtual Reality based eye diagnostic devices. While working with the rural community in India for his eye diagnostic prototype, Vaibhav founded ‘Makers Asylum.’ Maker’s Asylum is a community space focussed on fostering innovation through hands-on learning. The space houses various labs that are co-located in order to facilitate prototyping of ideas that are interdisciplinary in nature. Vaibhav essentially coupled his degree with his passion to create the first community Makerspace in India. The key focus of this space is to foster education in areas of sustainability and disability. The French President and the government has accredited him as a Young leader in this regard. In his leisure time Vaibhav enjoys making furniture, photography and winning at ping pong. He is also the Chair for innovation and entrepreneurship at Young Indians – Confederation of Indian Industries and a Global Shaper at the World Economic Forum. Currently, Vaibhav is on a mission to provide 1 Million face shields to healthcare and frontline workers to fight against COVID19.   Nitesh K. Jangir is a co-founder of Coeo Labs, a medical device company solving unmet clinical needs in the field of emergency and critical care. VAPCare is one of the products which he has developed at Coeo. VAPCare is a patented device to reduce chances of contracting ventilator-associated pneumonia (VAP), a fatal lung infection which kills more than 250,000 patients in India alone. His work has won many awards including MassChallenge Boston, Millennium Alliance, 3M Young Innovators Award, ASME I-Show, American College of Cardiology, 1776, Tata Social Enterprise Challenge etc.

column2: Global perspectives on Covid-19: Juan Pablo Trujillo
column8: Based in Argentina, Juan Pablo Trujillo is the Board Member, Director & Owner Pampa Capital Management LLP, and Pampa Capital Investors LLP, since 2008. Juan Trujillo has an ownership stake in Pampa Capital of between 10% and 25%. Pampa Capital Management LLP operates as a private equity investment firm, with a focus on agriculture, logistics, and technology companies, serving clients worldwide.

column2: Embracing renewable energy in post COVID-19 world: Balki Iyer
column8: Balakrishnan G. Iyer (Balki) is a seasoned energy and utilities industry management professional, with a rich experience in driving business development for global conglomerates. Iyer has successfully steered three start-ups from inception to exit, with investments from some of the largest utilities and financial investors worldwide. He is the Co-founder and Chief Growth Officer of Utopus Insights, a New York-based global renewable energy analytics company, recently acquired by Vestas. Starting his career at Schlumberger; Iyer has previously served as COO of renewable energy giant, Enel Green Power and as VP, Business Development at GE, where he drove technology developments for renewable energy and smart grid. He is passionate about the role of education and clean energy in changing the world, and over the last decade his business and entrepreneurial pursuits have been guided by this end. Along with his wife, he co-founded Iyer Educational Institutions (IEI) with the mission to offer inclusive learning opportunities for children with autism. He is on the advisory group for INK and was part of the Executive Board for GE’s Asia Pacific American Forum – a diversity group focused on mentoring Asian American business leaders.

column2: India's medical preparedness to fight the COVID: Vishal Rao
column8: Dr.Vishal Rao is presently the Chief of Head neck surgical oncology and robotic surgery at HealthCare Global Cancer centre Bangalore, India. He is a TEDx speaker and inventor of the Aum Voice Prosthesis a 1$ speaking device for throat cancer patients - an innovation that has been considered among the 100 global social innovations across the globe and received wide recognition from BBC, Harvard Business Review and Forbes. He has more than 13 patents filed for his innovations on medical devices, drugs, techniques and theories.

column2: India’s lockdown strategy: Dr. Vishal Rao
column8: Dr.Vishal Rao is presently the Chief of Head neck surgical oncology and robotic surgery at HealthCare Global Cancer centre Bangalore, India. He is a TEDx speaker and inventor of the Aum Voice Prosthesis a 1$ speaking device for throat cancer patients - an innovation that has been considered among the 100 global social innovations across the globe and received wide recognition from BBC, Harvard Business Review and Forbes. He has more than 13 patents filed for his innovations on medical devices, drugs, techniques and theories.

column2: What are our laws in the time of a pandemic? : K V Dhananjay
column8: K V Dhananjay is an advocate in practice at the Supreme Court and the Karnataka High Court. He has presented and argued a number of cases involving public health throughout his two decades of legal practice. He was instrumental in arguing for the 85% pictorial warning on tobacco packs in the Courts
column9: recent studies have shown that a vast majority of tobacco consumers have taken serious note of the pictorial warning and a recent survey (2016-17) by the Government of India did show that nearly 81 lakh tobacco consumers had quit it when compared with the previous survey (2009-10)
column10: most of those who quit are believed to have been sensitised to the danger of tobacco through such pictorial warnings. He has further fought for the prohibition of chewing tobacco in the State of Karnataka. He writes extensively in the print media - both English and Kannada. He often appears on television on matters of law and public interest. He has been actively campaigning for greater government measures to curb Covid-19.

column2: Food industry in times of Covid: Pooja Dhingra
column8: Pooja Dhingra is the founder of Le15 Patisserie and Studio Fifteen Culinary Centre in Mumbai. Pooja has also opened her first cafe at Colaba in 2016 called Le15 Cafe in collaboration with a culinary school friend called Pablito Naranjo. Armed with a degree in hospitality from Cesaz Ritz College, Switzerland and a Patisserie Diploma from Le Cordon Bleu. Pooja returned home with the single goal of creating Parisian styled culinary experiences in India.She has been featured in national dailies and is a regular in fashion and lifestyle glossies not just for her abilities in the kitchen but also as a dynamic businesswoman and inspiration to women - she was selected by Forbes India for their '30 Under 30' achievers list for 2014 and the Forbes 30 under 30 Asia list.

column2: Sabika Abbas Naqvi: Reclaiming public spaces through poetry
column8: Sabika Abbas Naqvi is a Performative Poet and the founder of ‘Sar-e-Rahguzar: Poetry on the Streets’. Her work revolves around intersectionality, gender, minority, LGBTQI+, and other progressive rights. Naqvi writes in Urdu, Hindi, Hindustani, and English and believes in subverting public spaces with her poetry and storytelling. As an educator she helps create and translate nclusive school curriculums based on social and emotional learning. She is a campaigner, and soon to be author, with two books swt to be released shortly. She currently works at change.org.Recorded at INK2019, Jaisalmer

column2: Inge De Lathauwer: Turning Tourism into a Force for Good
column8: Inge De Lathauwer is the Founder and Chairwoman of the Board of Trustees of the Sumba Hospitality Foundation, that provides a blueprint for responsible tourism with local communities at its heart. Her Foundation has built a vocational hotel school with a unique eco-resort and permaculture learning farm in Sumba, one of the poorest islands in Indonesia. Lathauwer’s mission is to provide students with a rigorous education in hospitality, as well as nurture their responsibilities to the beautiful natural environment.Recorded at INK2019, Jaisalmer

In that deep guttural desert voice, Kaki sings songs of valour and love. Unadorned by superfluous musical instruments, her voice reaches out and barrels up towards the bright sky. Aptly named the ‘Songstress of the Thar’ she begins her rituals as the sun begins to gently ebb over the horizon at the hour known as gao dhuli, a beautiful metaphor describing the onset of the evening when the dust rises, darkening the sky, thrown up by the returning cattle. Kaki is a legend in her environs.

column2: Meeta Pandit: Taking classical music to the masses
column8: A leading Hindustani classical vocalist, Meeta Pandit belongs to the Gwalior Gharana. She is the sixth in an unbroken lineage, and the first woman in the family to take up music professionally. She is the granddaughter and disciple of Padma Bhushan Pt Krishnarao Shankar Pandit, the 20th century doyen of North Indian classical music, and daughter of Pt Laxman Krishnarao Pandit. A top grade artist of All India Radio FM, her rendering of various forms, sufi, thumri, devotional, and light genres, is equally soulful. Pandit has performed in over 25 countries, been part of several international collaborations, and given her voice for two internationally-acclaimed films – Silent Waters and No Man's Land. A Consultant at IGNCA, New Delhi, she has also been actively coaching and teaching budding classical singers from India and abroad, and has authored the book 'India's Heritage of Gharana Music: Pandits of Gwalior’. In 2005, the Public Service Broadcasting Trust and Prasar Bharati made a film about Pandit, titled ‘Meeta - Linking a Tradition with Today’. Pandit has a PHD in Music, and is the recipient of several prestigious awards.

column2: PC Musthafa: From Getting One Meal a Day to Feeding Millions with Minimal Waste
column8: Born in a remote village in Kerala, PC Mustafa was a school dropout who later did his Engineering in Computer Science from NIT Calicut and his MBA from IIM Bangalore. During his childhood, breakfast was a dream and getting three meals a day, a luxury. In 2006, he co-founded iD Fresh Food that currently employs 1500+ youngsters from rural India and is currently feeding millions with idles, dosas, and other healthy, fresh and preservative-free food on a daily basis. The unicorn brand’s latest invention, iD Squeeze-And-Fr Vada Batter earned accolades from across the globe. Musthafa has been lauded with many prestigious awards like India Today’s Make In India Award, JCI National Award, Vocational Excellence Award, IIM Distinguished Alumni Award, among others. He was invited to share his success story at Harvard Business School, MIT-Sloan and the UN. He is part of Indian Philanthropy Initiative and also works very closely with DIAV for the welfare of Army Martyrs kin. Musthafa is also part of the Prime Minister’s ‘Champions of Change’ team with a vision to build a new India by 2022. His idea of traffic system automation is part of ‘New India Synopsis.Recorded at INK2019, Jaisalmer

column2: Prashant Gade: Doing more with less
column8: Many of us grapple with the question of finding our purpose. Social entrepreneur Prashant Gade found his – in giving back to society, as he dedicated his time and energies in creating an affordable prosthetic arm, giving a new lease of life to hundreds who couldn’t dare to dream. Listen to his motivations that led him on this journey.Recorded at INK2019, Jaisalmer

column2: Mahesh Bhupathi & Lara Dutta: What makes a superstar
column8: ABOUT LARA DUTTA: Lara Dutta, is a model, actress, producer and entrepreneur. She debuted in Bollywood in 2005, and in 2011 had her first stint as a producer. Her production house, Bheegi Basanti Productions, is now set to make her digital production debut with an upcoming web series based on The Meadow, Adrian Levy and Cathy Scott-Clark's 2012 book. Dutta is also a yoga practitioner and recently successfully launched  her skincare range ‘Arias’.ABOUT MAHESH BHUPATHI: Internationally-acclaimed tennis player, Mahesh Bhupathi is a Padmashree awardee (2001) for his contribution to Indian cricket. Just two years after beginning his professional career, in 1997 he became the first Indian to win a Grand Slam tournament in mixed doubles. After a series of successive wins, in 1999, Bhupathi and Leander Paes became the world no. 1 doubles team. With his win at the Australian Open mixed doubles in 2006, he joined the elite group of eight tennis players who have achieved a career Grand Slam in mixed doubles. The following year, in 2007, he was awarded the Sports people for Change Karmaveer Puraskaar. He has also been honoured with the Davis Cup Commitment Award. One of the most dominant names in Indian sporting history, Bhupathi retired from professional tennis in 2016. Bhupathi is a part of the Board of Advisors of IIMUN and India’s current non-playing Davis Cup Captain.

column2: Samar Farooqui: Learning to trust oneself, through slacklining
column8: Samar Farooqui is a professional adventurer and a slackliner who has been unlocking the potential of human balance for a decade. Educated in Adventure Tourism from New Zealand, Farooqui is a pioneering figure for slacklining and highlining in India and the current "free solo highline" record holder of India. His journey on the slackline has been a centre of focus for many newspaper articles and TV shows in India and New Zealand. He is also the brain and brawn behind India's only highline festival as well as India's only trickling competition. Farooqui has travelled across the world to spread the sport of slacklining and highlining, teaching, conducting workshops, and performing for people from all walks of life, from corporate honchos to Syrian refugee kids

column2: Utkarsh Amitabh: The Power of Community
column8: Passionate about using technology to match talent and opportunities, Utkarsh Amitabh is the Senior Business Development Manager at Microsoft and the Founder of Network Capital, a global peer-mentoring and career-navigation platform with over 50,000 mentors active in 104 countries. He was part of the team that built India's first smart village, now recognised in the Prime Minister's book of pioneering innovations. Amitabh has an MBA from INSEAD where he was recognised as an Andy Burgess Scholar. He is a World Economic Forum Global Shaper, TEDx speaker, Penn Social Impact House Fellow, Raisina Young Fellow, and the Torchbearer of Ashoka University's Young India Fellowship. Amitabh has a weekly column with Mint, and his articles have been published by the World Economic Forum, Indian Express, The Economic Times, The Times of India, and Scroll. He is also a trained actor and played ‘Major Metcalf’ in the world's longest running play, The Mousetrap.

Delhi-based musician and INK Fellow Anurag Hoon is the co-founder and CEO of Manzil Mystics, a non-profit choir band that performs songs inspired by the poetry of Kabir. A Masters in Social Work and a Marketing & Sales degree from the US, original compositions. Thus far, Manzil Mystics has performed in over 25 schools, 20 colleges, and 200 organisations. Anurag has been singing verses of Kabir and Gandhi in folk-fusion for a decade, making original compositions with Manzil Mystics and setting up musical events in low-income schools to establish that music creates a happy and safe space for everyone. He has more than 8 years of experience in Development and Education as a social worker, wherein he led the Delhi-based organisation, Manzil Welfare Society, as its CEO for a year.

column2: Farhana and Farzana Haque: Breaking new ground while staying rooted
column8: ABOUT FARHANA HAQUE: Farhana Haque is the Group Director for Devices at Microsoft India, responsible for all OEM businesses and relationships. As a global sales strategist and a new-age technology enthusiast, Haque has been driving thought leadership in the IoT space, that included setting up an IoT line of business for Vodafone India. An active mentor for startups, she campaigns unlocking human potential. Outside work, Haque is passionate about philanthropy and supports several non-profits, with a particular focus on women and children. She is also an avid painter and enjoys travelling.ABOUT FARZANA HAQUE: Farzana Haque began her career with the TATA group as a management trainee and is now the Global Head for Strategic Group Accounts for TATA Consultancy Services. She is deeply invested in creating global brands and multi-billion dollar organisations out of India and serves on the Board of Mentors for School of Courage, a mentorship program for entrepreneurs to scale up and build Unicorns of their brands. Committed to getting more women on boards as well as providing more capital and mentorship to women entrepreneurs, Haque founded Stree Shakti. She is also the global brand ambassador for Catalyst for Women Entrepreneurs. She serves on the board of global women centric funds and is an investor in global women startups and organisations. Haque is one of the world’s leading voices and influencers on building large organisations, women empowerment, technology, youth development and education. She has been invited over the years to do plenary sessions and keynotes Harvard, Stanford, MIT, LBS and Wharton. She is also on the board of Glendale Academy -- that is helping build future leaders and is a patron of the Lincoln Centre for the Performing Arts and the Juilliard School in NYC. Haque works and divides her time between her homes in NYC and London and is also a mother of two boys.Recorded at INK2019, Jaisalmer

column2: Farhana and Farzana Haque:: Breaking new ground while staying rooted
column8: ABOUT FARHANA HAQUE: Farhana Haque is the Group Director for Devices at Microsoft India, responsible for all OEM businesses and relationships. As a global sales strategist and a new-age technology enthusiast, Haque has been driving thought leadership in the IoT space, that included setting up an IoT line of business for Vodafone India. column2: Albert Lin: The chance of rebirth should be distributed evenly
column8: While there are 40 million amputees around the world, only 5% have access to prosthetics. A piece of hardware that can change your life must not remain the privilege of the rich, argues Research Scientist Albert Lin! Narrating his journey as an amputee, he makes an open call for collaboration, outlining a very simple way in which each of us can give a new leash of life to those in need.

Shonali Bose is an internationally-acclaimed Indian film director, writer and film producer. Both her narrative feature films — ‘Amu’, and ‘Margarita with a Straw’ — opened to critically-acclaimed theatrical releases in India, North America and Japan. They have been screened in over 150 film festivals including TIFF and Berlinale and won over 50 prestigious international awards. The Sky is Pink is her third feature narrative. It had its premier at the Toronto International Film Festival in September 2019 where it was the only Asian film in the Gala Presentations. It opened theatrically in 25 countries on October 11 and is now on Netflix. Bose is also the author of a Penguin published novel based on her screenplay — Amu; making her the only Indian to releaser her own novel and feature film simultaneously. Bose has an MA in Political Science from Cambridge University and an MFA in Directing from the UCLA Film School. She lives between Los Angeles and Mumbai and is most proud of being the mother of her two sons — Ishan and Vivan.Recorded at INK2019, Jaisalmer

column2: Alexander Bard: The End of Capitalism
column8: Alexander Bard is a Swedish cyber-philosopher, music producer, television star and sought after international speaker. He has given lectures on the philosophical, sociological and economic implications of the digital revolution since the late 1990s, and has been a fundamental force in creating the Swedish music export sensation. As a social entrepreneur, Bard is deeply involved in a series of highly successful technology companies as well as spiritual and political projects. Bard studied Economic Geography at the Stockholm School of Economics in the 1980s while building a highly successful international career as a songwriter and record producer. In 1992, he co-founded Stockholm Records, which quickly achieved global success -- with bands like The Cardigans, A-Teens and Bards own Army of Lovers -- and in 1998 was sold to and integrated with universal music. Even as he was occupied with cyber-philosophy and activism, Bard found the time to create a hit No. 1 on records in Europe, Asia and North America as recently as 2013. He is, perhaps unsurprisingly, also a television celebrity in Scandinavia, as the tough judge on television shows like Swedish Idol and Sweden’s Got Talent. Bard has written five books together with media theorist Jan Söderqvist. The first three titles -- The Netocrats, The Global Empire and The Body Machines -- have been released together as The Futurica Trilogy and has been translated into over 20 languages. A fourth book, Syntheism -- Creating God in the Internet Age, released in 2014 and a fifth title, Digital Libido -- Sex, Power and Violence in the Network Society, released in 2018. In each book, Bard and Söderqvist create a brand new metaphysical system for the digital age, covering everything from the inner existential truths of the new physics to the radical utopian potential of participatory culture.Recorded at INK2019, Jaisalmer

column2: George Papandreou: What does it take to be a global leader?
column8: George A. Papandreou is a former Prime Minister of Greece (2009-2011) and a Member of Parliament with the Movement of Change, coalition of Greek progress parties. First elected as MP in 1981, he has served in many governmental posts. As Minister for Education (1994-1996), he founded the Greek Open University and promoted multicultural programs. As Minister of Foreign Affairs (1999-2004), he promoted peace building and European Integration in the Eastern Mediterranean and the Balkans and managed a breakthrough in Greek-Turkish relations. An active supporter of the information society and e-democracy, in 2003 Papandreou was elected as one of the “25 People who are Changing the World of Internet Politics.” In 2004, he was elected leader of PASOK in the part and country’s first open primary — a move highly symbolic of his commitment to participatory governance. Throughout his political career, he has championed human rights at home and abroad, and has actively sought to maximise citizen participation in governance through information technologies. Since 2006, he has been the President of the Socialist International, the largest global political family. Around the world, Papandreou has deployed ‘Green Diplomacy,’ calling for the protection of the environment and placing sustainable development at the epicentre of policy making and multilateral development. Recorded at INK2019, Jaisalmer

column2: Tiffany Brar: Invoking Hope and Creating Opportunities for the Blind
column8: Tiffany Brar is a special educator, accessibility trainer, social activist and a motivational speaker. Despite her visual disability, Brar steered ahead and completed her BA English, BED special education and started a mobile blind school where she travelled across Kerala in search of blind people, with the aim of transforming them from liabilities to assets. She then started Jyothigramaya Foundation, whose sole aim is empowerment and inclusion of the visually impaired. As an activist, she is committed to fighting for the rights of the blind community. She is an avid adventurer, having gone paragliding and skydiving — even enabling some of her students to do the same! Brar is a five-time TED speaker, a national award winner, and has also been appreciated by the late DR. APJ Abdul Kalam, former President of India, for her work. Recorded at INK2019, Jaisalmer

column2: Orin Hardy: The Ingenuity of Bamboo for Sustainability
column8: Orin Hardy is the co-founder of The Kul Kul Farm and Bamboo U, two hands on education enterprises in Bali. He dedicates his time to creating spaces and opening up new possibilities for people to learn how to incorporate sustainability into their lives. Combining his international expertise with local knowledge, Hardy facilitates and teaches courses related to hands-on living, permaculture design, gardening and bamboo construction. Along with his team, Hardy has welcomed hundreds of people from all over the world to participate in these programs. Raised in a Balinese village surrounded by rivers and jungle, he then moved to North America where he witnessed this disconnect between humans and nature in the modern world. He now spends his time devoted to reconnect people with nature. Recorded at INK2019, Jaisalmer

http://inktalks.com Setting small targets is a surefire way to get yourself used to winning, explains INK Fellow and entrepreneur Ritu Soni Srivastava at INK conference 2018. Watch it and turn the wheel of belief.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

http://inktalks.com In a heartening talk, INK Fellow Munaf Kapadia, the self-proclaimed Chief Eating Officer of The Bohri Kitchen, shows us how something as simple as a home dining experience can transform inter-community relationships in India.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: The youth must be part of the leadership
column8: http://inktalks.com Mentoring a young Kenyan girl (under the program Three Dot Dash) revealed to Jess Teutonico the power of the youth of today – a community more curious, connected and powerful than ever before. She shares how the relationship changed her, and calls upon us all to include young people in the leadership to see the positive impact needed in our neighbourhoods, companies and policies.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

http://inktalks.com INK Fellow Siddharth Nair gives a talk on how a personal situation led him to putting his education at test, developing a home healthcare model combining neuroscience and engineering. His attempt proving successful he is now on the journey of creating home healthcare machines that would be affordable and accessible for the needy.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: A world with knowledge and information set free
column8: http://inktalks.com As we reap the benefits of a digitally connected world today, it comes at a cost – of all our personal data being used for creating echo chambers to sell propaganda. In a stirring talk, Priya Kuber lays the ​case for building decentralized internet, free of net neutrality, censorship and fake news. Watch as she calls upon a movement to set knowledge and information free.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: Providing early health intervention in resource-poor settings
column8: http://inktalks.com INK Fellow Nitin Sisodia speaks about health issues in resource-poor settings due to lack of proper information and resources, particularly in new borns, and stresses on how early technological intervention can help many lead a better life.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

http://inktalks.com Watch as poet Bina Sarkar, fashion visionary Sangita Kathiwada, and musician Joi Barua come together for a soulful poetry reading session. The crisp 10-minute video shares poems from Bina Sarkar’s book,’ ‘When Seeing is Believing: Poetry in Images’ where she responds as a poet in verse to mesmerizing imagery of international artists and photographers.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: Technology to turn Tragedies into Triumph
column8: http://inktalks.com Scientist Ramesh Rao, along with young researcher Albert Yu-Min Lin, from UCSD shares how technology is being used to empower millions of amputees, as institutes like Qualcomm are helping them transform stories of tragedy into triumph.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: Unraveling the Microscopic World of DNA
column8: http://inktalks.com In an enriching talk, scientist and INK Fellow Anjana Badrinarayanan has us dive into the microscopic world of DNA, demonstrating the ability of life to be encoded in these minute structures, unraveling the wonders of science.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

http://inktalks.com There are nearly 250 cancer villages near China's polluted rivers, did you know? Charlene Ren (Founder, MyH2O Water Information Network) reveals her model of using 'citizen science' to connect clean water resources to rural communities and give them lives worth living. Listen in as she talks about lowering the barrier of the fluidity of resources and making unheard voices heard.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

http://inktalks.com We all have polarities in our personalities and professional lives. Entrepreneur and INK Fellow Vaibhav Lodha shares how and why must one balance these seeming opposing pulls to find a median and move towards the better.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: Using Blockchain Technology to create a Free Economy
column8: http://inktalks.com In a simple and lucid manner, certified Bitcoin professional Shikha Mehra breaks down the workings of blockchain technology, emphasizing its value towards the distribution of wealth with the users, rather than with monopolized establishments. She urges us to re-write the story of human collaboration by returning to the basics of direct transactions and a free economy.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

http://inktalks.com Did you know that at present human species conservatively spends 300 billion hours playing games. What makes them fun? In an exciting talk, storyteller and game-designer Zain Memon breaks this down with examples, establishing how gaming is the next step for storytelling and learning.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: Building India into a Product Nation
column8: Product Superstar Girish Mathrubootham defied many a conventional wisdom on entrepreneurship and built his SaaS startup Freshworks into a billion dollar company from India. In this compelling talk, he shares his learnings and his motivations; and his dream of building India into the next Silicon Valley. Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

In an impassioned talk, entrepreneur and national-level table tennis player, Vivek Bhargava takes aim at the societal pressure of ‘settling down’, arguing that it is no more than an epidemic, afflicting happiness and stunting lives. Sharing his personal journey, he establishes how life is better lived by keeping your passion alive.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

Silicon valley entrepreneur and technology geek, Nirman Dave pushed the boundaries of artificial intelligence to build a neural network that can predict irrational human behaviour. It leads him to question that, in the face of AI and machine learning advancements, what then remains uniquely human? Listen in to find out.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

Art is soft power – an indicator of who we are and what we can be. Gallerist Aparajita Jain gives a riveting and thought-provoking talk on India’s intangible art heritage and the indescribable value it holds. She questions, ‘what then is holding us back from appreciating, respecting and furthering it?Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

Music prodigy Navneeth Sundar combined his gift of music with his bent towards science, and gave birth to, a hitherto unheard of term, iPad musician. In a lively talk, Sundar shares his journey to discovering the delicate nuances of this new-age music and entering the Limca Book of Records for the first-ever classical concert played on an iPad.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

It is not a question of if but when an organization will be breached in cyberspace. In this talk, cybersecurity strategist Jonathan Reiber describes the vulnerable nature of the data-driven world in which we live -- and outlines specific steps that organizations can take to become secure beyond breach.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: Giving the LGBTQ community their due
column8: In a spirited talk, Human Rights Crusader and activist Anjali Gopalan shares her journey in fighting India’s long-standing battle to decriminalize homosexuality. ‘Your sexuality is who you are, and if that is denied to you, what are you left with?, she argues. Her story urges us on with courage in standing for what we believe in and to never give up. On 6 September 2018, the Supreme Court of India decriminalised homosexuality by declaring Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code unconstitutional.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: Sister Jesme: Find the Power Within You
column8: In an emphatic and emotional talk, Dr Sister Jesme, shares the shocking revelation of the hollowness of religious institutions, sending across the message to find power and courage within you, than without. Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: Hanif Kureshi: Reclaiming the streets to create art for all
column8: In an enlivening talk, multidisciplinary artist and designer Hanif Kureshi throws light on the invaluable local sensibility inherent in street art, and shares his journey to preserving the same, using the power of walls to create art for all.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

Exuding beauty and grace, Kuchipudi dancer Haleem Khan mesmerizes with his performance, breaking all barriers of convention, gender and religion in pursuit of art, passion and life – inspiring us all to settle for nothing less than our dreams.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: Ankit Agarwal: Be the change you want to see
column8: It takes real grit and courage to take it upon yourself to change what seems inevitably insurmountable and beyond you! Ankit Agarwal does exactly this as he sets about cleaning the river Ganges of its gigantic amounts of temple waste that is steadily killing the ecosystem. He further breaks barriers by employing marginalized women and giving them the dignity long denied to them. Listen in as he inspires by example to take action and create the larger-than-life impact you wish to see happen!Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: Yang Shih Hao: The Cyr-wheel Wonder
column8: In a magical performance, Yang Shih-Hao sways with his Cyr wheel, with such grace and finesse that seems to infuse it with a life of its own. Watch as he moves effortlessly, transporting you to a space where every moment counts. Performance recorded at ‘INK2018: Billionaires of Moments’, held in HyderabadABOUT YANG SHIH HAO: Yang Shih Hao went viral when his performance with the Cyr wheel hit the web, grossing an immense twenty million views. Originally specializing in hat juggling, Yang went from an being an attendant in the Hong Kong coliseum to a performer on the streets of Taiwan, and is now a member of the esteemed Cirque Eloize. His performance is graceful and seems almost gravity-defying. He has devoted seven years of his life to performing in the circus, touring over twenty countries, showcasing his talent at international circus festivals across the globe.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: Gary Bencheghib: Be Bold in Fighting What You Believe In
column8: The young founder of ‘Make A Change World’, environment activist Gary Bencheghib, inspires by example. Canoeing down the Citarum, deemed the world’s most polluted river, on kayaks made from plastic bottles, he and his brother got the government to take notice, impacting policy change to save the environment! ‘Be bold in fighting what we believe in’ is the powerful message he sends across. Talk recorded at ‘INK2018: Billionaires of Moments’ in HyderabadABOUT GARY BENCHEGHIB: INK Fellow Gary is an environmental-and-water activist, and filmmaker. His foundation, Make a Change World, uncovers uplifting and inspirational stories with an aim to give a voice to the underrepresented and bring about social change. With his younger brother Sam Bencheghib, he has launched a series of expeditions – from kayaking the world’s most polluted river in Java on plastic-bottle kayaks, to standup paddling down New York’s most toxic waterways – to bring to light the impact of growing water pollution. In the past 2 years, Gary’s videos have been viewed by over 500 million people worldwide.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: Devdutt Pattanaik: What Makes us Valuable?
column8: In an insightful talk, mythologist Devdutt Pattanaik makes a charming connect, establishing how the four purusharthas - artha, kama, dharma, moksha – of Hinduism provide a framework to the order of the universe, centred around value creation for the self and other. Talk recorded at ‘INK2018: Billionaires of Moments’, held in HyderabadABOUT DEVDUTT PATTANAIK: Devdutt Pattanaik writes on the relevance of mythology in modern times, especially in areas of management, governance and leadership. Trained in medicine, he worked for 15 years in healthcare and pharma industries before focussing on his passion full time. He has authored 30 books and 600 columns, including bestsellers such as My Gita, Jaya, Sita, Business Sutra and the 7 Secret Series. He was a speaker at TEDIndia 2009 and spoke on Myths that Mystify, East versus West. His TV shows include Business Sutra on CNBC-TV18 and Devlok on Epic TV. He consults organisations on culture, diversity and leadership, and various television channels and filmmakers on storytelling.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: Stefania Magidson: Blueprint for Social Entrepreneurship
column8: In a soul-stirring talk, philanthropist Stefania Magidson shares a new blueprint for social entrepreneurship to help the disadvantaged alienate their future from their past. She shares her personal journey that led her to the work she’s involved with, and its far-reaching rewards. Talk recorded at ‘INK2018: Billionaires of Moments’ in HyderabadABOUT STEFANIA MAGIDSON: A global citizen dedicated to empowering her fellow human beings, Magidson is creating a new blueprint for social entrepreneurship through her constant endevours. She heads one of the largest non-profit organizations in the Romanian diaspora, Blue Heron Foundation, giving the disadvantaged youth an access to life-changing opportunities. Her book “Searching for the White Magician” is a series of dialogues explores themes close to her, ranging from immigration and philanthropy to spiritual psychology and self-realization.ABOUT INK: INKtalks is committed to capturing and sharing breakthrough ideas, inspiring stories and surprising perspectives – across diverse fields! Personal narratives that hit straight to the heart in 18 minutes or less. Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

In a powerful talk, writer-producer Wendy Calhoun inspires a worldview of inclusion, compelling each one of us to use the yardstick of empathy both for ourselves and others. She demonstrates the same through her on-screen characters, created to underline diversity and gender equality.  Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

Watch as Bharat Kaul (Director, Intel Labs-India) gives a fascinating talk on transformational technology, on how it has changed the graph of history and on using it to shape our tomorrow.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: Technology for Good is the way ahead
column8: Watch as technology creates magic and underlines how innovation can accelerate societal transformation, bringing about solutions that are sensible, responsible and explainable.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

INK Conference 2018 brought the deep-tech godfather Tony Fadell to India for the first time! Listen in as, in an interview with CEO Lakshmi Pratury, the inventor of iPod, co-inventor of iPhone, and founder of Nest, Fadell shares insights into the birth of disruptive products and ideas, and what goes into making an entrepreneurial journey successful.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

In a stirring talk, Sunny Singh, founder of RoundGlass makes us pause and reflect upon the epidemic facing us all today – of the modern lifestyle. He urges us all to live the slow life, to be grateful, build meaningful relationships and make wholistic wellbeing the journey of life. Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

Warm and informal, and interspersed with witty anecdotes, this inaugural address by the Hon’ble Vice President of India, Shri M Venkaiah Naidu at INK2018 celebrates India’s entrepreneurial potential, and urges innovators and creators to use technology for social good. Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

In a compelling talk, teen fiction author Zuni Chopra talks about fighting the privilege she’s born with, of celebrity parentage, to be recognized for her own mettle. ‘What mountain can you conquer to match the Everest of those who came before you?, compels one to think.

Singer and storyteller Usha Uthup takes the INK stage by storm singing songs on ‘shoes’, thanking her cobblers Sushil and Misri Das for her distinct ‘Kanjeevaram sneakers’ that have come to define her style over the years.Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD
Recorded at INK2018, HYDERABAD

column2: Dr. Romesh Wadhwani shares his Entrepreneurial journey
column8: Recorded at INK salon, Mumbai

In a crisp and uplifting talk, entrepreneur Shravya Reddy shares simple yet ingenious ideas that must be incorporated in the present (and archaic) education system to rekindle the joy for learning and teaching. Her talk reveals essential building blocks that go beyond just an engaging curriculum and infrastructure Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

In an evocative talk, social entrepreneur Ankit Durga brings to light the much-needed overhaul in the Indian education system needed to train students to be self-starters. He shares stories of courage in circumstance that served as the behind his enterprise, Leap Skills Academy, aimed at bridging this essential gap in education.

column2: Humans and AI to save the world
column8: Watch as Kalyan Veeramachaneni, a Principal Research Scientist at MIT, delves into the realm of AI, discussing challenges in using it to the optimum and predicting close interaction between the humans and AI in near-future.Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

column2: Use your time like a miser
column8: INK Fellow Advait Gupt takes aim at the current digital age that, with an overflow of information has made time our most valuable resource. He challenges us to, here on, make a conscious choice of how and where we spend this resource. Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

column2: How about coffee with an inanimate companion
column8: Pioneering surgeon Susan Lim takes the audience on an engrossing journey of imagination, delving into the possibility of inanimates becoming intelligent companions to humans in the near future. Not a science fiction or fantasy she demonstrates, through a series of anecdotes and factual data; reminding us that robots are already commanding jobs where patience and precision are key. Are we ready for this alternative reality?Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

In this compelling talk, MIT Media Lab's Judith Amores shows us how she is using technology to shape human perception and enhance the power of mind for us to become more mindful.ABOUT INK: INKtalks are personal narratives that get straight to the heart of issues in 18 minutes or less. We are committed to capturing and sharing breakthrough ideas, inspiring stories and surprising perspectives--for free!Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

In a thought-provoking talk, RMZ Foundation’s AN Venugopal shares insights on the need and ease of weaving philanthropy into the corporate work culture. Drawing examples from the Foundation’s project for construction labour – giving them avenues of recreation and volunteering, instilling a sense of social responsibility, and thereby creating a happy environment – he demonstrates how ‘going beyond boundaries gives abundance’. Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

Entrepreneur Travis Wu talks of the power of storytelling in bringing humanity together. He demonstrates how Virtual Reality can help us tell stories and must be used for that end! For, as human beings ‘what we really crave is not entertainment, but being understood by one another.’Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

column2: See the wonder in the familiar
column8: Listen in to artist Dia Mehta as she reminds us to pause and appreciate the familiar. ‘It’s the repetitiveness of our day to day makes us who we are’. She demonstrates this in her own craft, recreating everyday spaces using recycled paper. Recorded at Road to GES 2017Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

In an enlivening conversation with Lakshmi Pratury (CEO, INKtalks), Chennaiyin FC co-owner Vita Dani shares her journey, starting with an accidental encounter with sports to owning and promoting not one but two major leagues, in football and table tennis. ‘No matter how much you do in sports, it is never enough, and it is never enough fun; you always want more’, says the inspired promoter. Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

column2: There will be no robot apocalypse
column8: Watch as robotics expert Reiko Yasue demonstrates how the soft robotics of ‘Big Heroes 6’ (2014-animation movie) is already enmeshed in the present and is not futuristic. And yet, she debunks the idea of a potential humanoid robot apocalypse, sighting their shortcomings. ‘We create the robots and we create the future’ is her confident stance.Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

column2: The Art of Being an Idiot
column8: ‘Be an idiot and admit you don’t have knowledge’, asserts Gary Mao. Tune into this young entrepreneur’s spirited talk on how just by listening and observing he entered a sector he had no clue about, turned problems into opportunity and sought the impact he could make on the worldRecorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

Hear the dashing Indian actor R. Madhavan talk to the CEO of INK Lakshmi Pratury on how constant change is necessary for innovation to happen in India and how everything we do teaches us something, be it success or failure. “All you need as entrepreneurs is to find that tune.”Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad
Watch and listen to a fun VC Roast of a bunch of venture capitalists, led by Jay Krishnan, CEO of T-Hub.Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

Devi Murthy talks about how her brainchild ‘Kamal Kisan’ has created simple solutions in agri- business with the help of technology, and how that has redefined the industry by creating smart farmers, optimising their resources.Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

Farid Ahsan, CEO of ShareChat, gave a riveting talk on how his app has helped create a platform to reach out to millions across India, irrespective of language and geographical barriers. Like Lakshmi said, “Sharechat is all about vernacular beauty!”Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

Jai Natarajan talks about how his company iMerit employs mostly people from low-income backgrounds and empowers them to work with advanced systems like image tagging for self-driving cars, image segmentation for VR and AR, cancer cell categorisation for medical diagnosis, Fintech and more.Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

column4: ['Dr. P. Raghu Ram', 'Raghu Gullapalli', 'Dr. Ananda Shankar Jayant']
column8: Dr. P. Raghu Ram, Director, KIMS-USHALAKSHMI Centre for Breast Diseases and his patient, the classical dancer Ananda Shankar Jayant, talk about the importance of counselling in treating cancer, as otherwise it wages war not only on your body, but on your mind. Raghu Gullapalli, Executive Director of Emerging Technologies, L.V. Prasad Eye Institute, also weighs in on the technologies available to create solutions for visual disorders in India today.Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

column2: Health is a by-product of enlightenment
column8: People often sacrifice health for a little wealth, and eventually start living on borrowed time. How do we change that?Listen to Dr. Suhas Kshirsagar, Director of Ayurvedic Healing Inc., talk about ways to effect a healthy lifestyle change, through better eating and sleeping patterns.Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

column2: Science is a quest to understand
column8: "I personally do science because it is beautiful like art. Beauty is truth and for me, my truth is science". Physicist Prerna Sharma studies cell membranes. Listen to her talk on the need and importance of basic science for ground-breaking discoveries that can push us beyond boundaries.Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

"We believe that there is no reason for anyone to build diesel ferry boats". Sandith Thandasherry, CEO of NavAlt Solar and Electric Boats, speaks about launching the world’s first Solar Ferry that carries thousands of passengers in the backwaters of Kerala.Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

Be mesmerised by the 26 year old “Wireless Walking Violinist” Aneesh Vidyashankar as he holds you spellbound with his delicate rendition of Indian movie songs.Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

Prabhat Labh, CEO of Grameen Foundation India, spoke about the 3 major barriers in achieving financial inclusiveness i.e. capacity barrier, trust barrier and access barrier, and steps one can take to overcome it. Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

Listen to a fun panel with three of our INK Fellows, Pooja Dhingra, Yash Dongre and Somdev Devvarman talking about their journeys in food, fashion and sports respectively. Each of them are truly aiming for the stars!Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

Vikram Kailas of Mytrah Energy and Vanitha of IBM India in a very optimistic discussion with Lakshmi Pratury, on changes in the power industry due to the technological advancements and opportunities that come along with it, making available a platform for small entrepreneurs due to de-marketization.Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

Saad Nasser, the science prodigy and Aditi Avasthi, Founder of Embibe, have a revealing panel discussion with Sunil Rao of Lightspeed, on self-learning AI machines and using data science for tailoring children's education. Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

"Lets begin a symbiotic relationship with AI, where it thrives on our unstructured data, and we on its efficiency". Nivruti Rai, General Manager of Intel India talks on how a massive amount of unstructured data exists in our country, making it the perfect hotspot for AI mining . Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

Hailing from a family with blindness in their genes, Shekhar Naik gives a touching talk on how he developed a deep passion for the cricket sport, eventually receiving the prestigious Padmashree award in the year 2017 for his dedication and contribution towards Blind Cricket.Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

“Ever since I was a child, my goal was to land up in Mars“. Gadadhar Reddy, CEO of NoPo Nanotechnologies India, shares with us how NoPo (which ironically stands for “Not Possible”), develops nanotubes and is all set to develop Nano Satellites by 2019. Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

Nobel Peace Prize winner Kailash Satyarthi appeals to the leaders of tech force today to find technological solutions to societal problems and stresses on how basic facilities like healthcare and education should not become a commodity.Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

Eisenhower Fellow and MD of Accenture Labs India Sanjay Podder gives a revealing talk on creating technology for good, expanding on instances where tech start-ups today have created models to avoid vulnerability of human trafficking with the use of AI. Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

Listen to Amitabh Kant (CEO of NITI Aayog), Navtej Sarna (Indian Ambassador to the US) and R. Madhavan (Actor) - gamechangers from three different worlds - come together and talk about how India can mine into its great repository of resources, create innovators to solve problems and emerge winners at the intersection of entrepreneurship, policy and technologyRecorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

column2: No one can stop an idea whose time has come
column8: The Hon’ble Sri Kalvakuntla Taraka Rama Rao, Industries and IT Minister of Telangana, speaks about the power of ideas and what India needs today — our own local solutions catered to the diversity and challenges that lie before us, unique to our society alone. He stresses on how we do not need venture capitalists but ‘adventure capitalists’, and outlines a 3D mantra -  Digitize, Decarbonize and Decentralize for a paradigm shift.The Minister certainly was the headliner of Road to GES: Beyond Boundaries, ending his talk with a inspiring quote, “The best way to predict the future is to create it. We live in an age of uncertainty where ideas are the only tools to help”. Listen and be enthralled by his powerful oration!Recorded at Road to GES 2017, Hitex Exhibition Centre, Hyderabad

column2: From starting Infosys to saving water
column8: Philanthropist Rohini Nilekani talks to Lakshmi Pratury about setting up Infosys in the early 90’s, her attempt to encourage children to read more books and about her Foundation Arghyam, which works with water and sanitation issues.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

At INK2013, the legendary singer Usha Uthup gives a performance of a lifetime. For the first time ever, Uthup is joined on stage by her daughter and granddaughter for some foot-tapping, soulful music. Recorded at INK2013, Kochi, Kerala

Young business magnate Keshav Reddy gives a candid talk on his initiation into the Indian conglomerate GVK's airport operations, and the single idea that changed his perspective on the meaning of 'scale'.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

column2: Finding my way back to health
column8: As an entrepreneur Vishal Gondal built India’s largest gaming company, but lost his health along the way. At INK2014, Gondal shares how he hacked his way back to fitness.Recorded at INK2014, Mumbai

Growing up in Iran, Anousheh Ansari dreamt of going into space just like on Star Trek, and in September 2006 she became the first woman private space explorer travelling to and staying onboard of ISS. Sharing an awe-inspiring video of her flight to space, Ansari talks about the mind-boggling technology advancements to expect in the coming decades, and reminds us that the future is what we imagine it to be.Recorded at INK Asia 2015, Singapore
Founder and CEO of OYO Ritesh Agarwal shares his journey on scaling up OYO; from what it was to where it is now – the 14th largest hotel chain in the world.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Unsettled by his grandmother losing her memory, Dheeraj decided to study how memories can be retrieved in the brain. Listen as he takes us through his scientific research to find a more targeted cure for Alzheimer’s disease.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Urban farmer Allan Lim gives a spirited talk on the power of sustainable farming in bringing a community together and his journey in engaging Singaporeans of all ages to adopt it as a meaningful way of life.Recorded at INK Asia 2016, Singapore

Taiwanese entrepreneur turned politician Jason Hsu talks of his mission to use technology, innovation and education to maximise the do-good influence on society. As he says, '' I don't want to be outside the castle anymore, just watching it. I want to get in there, throw weapons into it and create change".Recorded at INK Asia 2016, Singapore

column2: The next tech for the smart-everything era
column8: Goa-born researcher Andrea Colaco shows us what she has in store for consumer tech. With digital devices shrinking from bulky desktops to wearable accessories, how will we interact with technology in the future? Andrea demonstrates her work on these evolving interfaces, which work on what comes most naturally to human communication -- hand gestures. Recorded at INK2013, Kochi, Kerala

Vinay Venkatraman gives us a glimpse into the world of streetside tinkering shops, where salvaged electronic parts are reconfigured and retrofitted to serve a new function. Venkatraman has brought this approach into creating ingenious digital solutions -- alarm clocks made into medical screening devices, low cost projectors, and a hearing loss-screening device using a smartphone, which he demonstrates here.Recorded at INK2012, Pune, India

INK Fellow Saba Ghole echoes the wisdom of Zen Master Shunryo Suzuki on cultivating a Beginner's Mind in her approach to creativity and innovation. Ghole gives us a glimpse into NuVu Studios, an innovation studio she leads for middle and high school students where multi-disciplinary collaboration, experimentation, reinvention, and creativity are the core values.Recorded at INK2012, Pune, India

Surprisologist Tania Luna believes that amazing things can happen if we let the surprise in to our lives. When something unexpected happens, it triggers the surprise sequence in our brains -- surprises truly enrich our lives. Watch as Luna shares fascinating insights and offers ways we can let the surprise in.Recorded at INK2012, Pune, India

Nancy Margried talks to us about the history of the Indonesian Batik print and her efforts to empower the traditional Batik artisans through innovative software tools and skills.Recorded at INK Asia 2016, Singapore

column2: There can be poetry in policy
column8: Policy maker Aaron Maniam puts forth an eloquent talk on his deep love for poetry and how he intertwines it with his passion for public policy.Recorded at INK Asia 2016, Singapore

Artist, Subodh Kerkar puts the spotlight on the fanasticsm many traditional Indians have against anything from abroad – holding strong beliefs that we need to redefine and refabricate the country and it’s patriots. In this witty, eye-opening talk he takes us on a journey to understanding where the so-called ‘traditional’ food we eat really comes from. Recorded at INK2016, Goa

column2: Insurance is the love letter we write to our families
column8: "How do we increase insurance penetration?" Rani Paruchuri talks about how being insured helped her through a difficult period in her childhood and why she eventually chose insurance as a domain to tackle as an entrepreneur.Recorded at INK Asia 2016, Singapore

In conversation with Lakshmi, physician Larry Brilliant recounts how he followed his spiritual guru's missive to join WHO in the fight to eradicate smallpox, his travels around India in pursuit of that goal and his work with the Seva Foundation and Google.Recorded at INK Salon 2015, Delhi

column4: ['Akshay Nanavati', 'Nirali Kartik', '', 'Shannon Olsson', 'Sanvar Oberoi', 'Vicky Roy', 'Krushnaa Patil']
column8: Hear some amazing game changers recount their INK Fellow experience and tell YOU why you should apply for the Fellows Program this year!

Philanthropist and VC Kamran Elahian talks about two mega trends which affect world economy – falling oil prices, and sustainable consumption.  He goes on to show how spread of terrorism is linked to unemployment and discusses BIT AMENA, his vision to create 10 million innovation jobs in 10 years.Recorded at INK Asia 2016, Singapore

column2: What does it mean to be old?
column8: “We old people are never too old to learn, to change and start new businesses from scratch”. Founder of Beautiful Years, Vladi Ruppo, gives us a picture on what is the status of aging today and how to help the elderly bring meaning into their lives.Recorded at INK Asia 2016, Singapore

column2: A talent pool that cannot be ignored
column8: Neha Bagaria recounts her journey of shifting back from a full-time mom to a working mom, and tells us how she started Jobsforher - a platform to help women on a career break get back into the job scene and ‘re-skill’ themselves.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Accompanied by harmonica player Dev, musician Ananth Menon gives a foot-tapping guitar performance of a blues song, followed by a more somber but melodious song concerning the economic depression post-1920.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

In a revealing conversation with Lakshmi, businessman Thomas John Muthoot gives us a rare glimpse into his company’s financial holdings and talks about working with low income customers to help ease their financial burdens.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Activist Sunitha Krishna shakes the audience with a powerful talk on her fight against the rapists of the world, her campaign to get the crimes reported and offenders arrested, and a passionate call to action.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Simulatenously sharing intriguing global examples, President of Cisco Smart+Connected Communities Anil Menon gives a passionate talk on rethinking all the things that today have an impact on ecology, healthcare, energy and water consumption in our world.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Former Cirque du Soleil artist, Jesko von den Steinen, talks about his magnum opus, the “House of Dancing Water” and his journey taking the iterative human process from theatre and bringing it in to business and brand.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Goan Fadista Sonia Shirsat gives us a little peek into the history of “Fado” music, a form of song originating from Portugal. Listen to her perform a light but soulful rendition of a Fado song and a Goan dekhni song.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Swetha Suresh talks about the various accolades she has won for her record-breaking whistling skills and goes on to enchant the audience with two astounding whistling performances – one Mozart composition and the other, an Indian Carnatic composition.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Displaying the vibrant techniques of Kalaripayattu combat on stage, recent Padma Shri awardee Meenakshi Raghavan and her family take us through her fascinating journey to become a 'kalari' and the rich history and culture of this ancient martial art.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Grammy award winning composer Ricky Kej talks about climate change, an issue he is passionate about and his various musical efforts encouraging people to take it seriously. He also reveals how a conversation with Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi inspired him to create an album for the United Nations Climate Change Conference.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

column2: The key for India is radical change
column8: Indian Government official and CEO of NITI Aayog Amitabh Kant talks passionately with Lakshmi Pratury on his part in the “Incredible India” campaign, his dynamic efforts with the state education systems and his unshakable faith in India's potential to innovate and urbanize.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Drawing on his fascination for Rudyard Kipling’s work during his childhood, science photographer and researcher Prasenjeet Yadav talks about how he bridges the gap between scientists and non-scientists using photography as a method of storytelling. Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Full of exuberance and insight, Sekou Andrews uses his Poetic Voice style of speaking to deliver a whirlwind talk that takes us on a 5-step journey toward creating “New Money.” The audience delights in the discomfort of saying “This year it’s about the money!” as this interactive and entertaining talk charges us to move our concept of money from our pockets to our minds, hearts and hands, because “real wealth is not whether I can pay for it, but whether I can pay it forward."Recorded at INK2016, Goa

In this candid conversation between Lakshmi Pratury and Indian politician Shashi Tharoor, he delves into his decision to join politics, his 29-year career at the UN, and his thoughts pertaining to the British colonization of India.

column2: Music as a tool for social empowerment
column8: Lover of music Luis Dias delivers a passionate talk on the inception of Child’s Play India Foundation, a charity which works to bring classical music to underprivileged children in India, ending with his students performing a lovely orchestra on stage.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

In conversation with Lakshmi, the “Guru of Indian cuisine” Kumar Mahadevan talks about his deeply personal interpretations of the five senses of taste as well as his experience on the sets of ‘Masterchef Australia’Recorded at INK2016, Goa

column2: Combining the old with the new in design
column8: Anubhav Gupta talks with Lakshmi on what in design inspires him, how the Godrej Experience Center was repurposed from old factory buildings and the interactive art installations called “Cabinets of Curiosity” which reside there.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Creative Director and Founder of Synn Labs, Adam Sadowsky, talks about his company and how they combine science, art and technology to construct visually dynamic content for brands.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Gaurav Hinduja, cofounder of online lending platform Capital Float, talks about the future of SME lending where people can get a loan online. He takes the audience on a step-by-step journey of how that goal can be achieved with the technology he is creating.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Sandhya Goli talks about how her journey playing chess started and how her parents, despite their middle class background and criticism from society, helped her to dream - leading her to win multiple medals across the world.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

‘To create a great company that creates great impact, you should be building rather than selling’. In this talk, Naukri.com’s Sanjeev Bikhchandani gives the audience a few pointers on smart entrepreneurship and scaling up.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

column2: Making healthcare accessible, printable and deployable
column8: MIT Media Lab’s Pratik Shah wants to move towards a future where healthcare is exclusive for everyone. In this talk, he tells us about innovative imaging technologies which use biomarkers in our body for on-site diagnostics. Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Musician Jill Sobule gives a charming and witty performance of a song she wrote about the history of immigration in America. She goes on to sing a few more of her songs, all which carry important messages.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Harshit Agarwal talks about the different tools and technologies that he's creating to help people immerse themselves in their creations and let their imaginations take flight in quirky ways.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Anshul Tewari started  'Youth Ki Awaaz' to motivate young people to speak up. In this talk, he tells us about how his platform has encouraged different forms of issue-based writing, saved lives and given rise to social media movements.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

column2: Is Mahatma Gandhi even relevant today?
column8: Celebrated environmentalist and Gandhian, Anupam Mishra [1948 – 2016] reflects on the modern society in this moving talk at INK2011 in Jaipur. Commenting on education, wars, and living for the weekend, Mishra leaves us with a beautiful metaphor to look for solutions rather than the problems that surround us. Recorded at INK2011, Jaipur, India

Activist Heather Blair speaks passionately on how to eradicate the 'silence' surrounding the topic of sexual assault and the need to use the power of social media to foster an environment that encourages people to share.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Not knowing what his passion was early on in life, Sameer finally realized what he likes to do best is to eat! Listen to him talk about his journey towards opening his dream restaurant ‘The Bombay Canteen’.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

column2: Why is Blockchain a game changer?
column8: Gavin shares what the Blockchain is, how and why it is going to change the world and how it has managed to commoditize the rarest of all intangible assets: trust.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

In his informative talk, Jeroen van de Waal tackles the worldwide problem of obesity and unveils ‘Rise Ebove’, a bicycle simulator which is designed to simulate real-life riding on a bicycle by combining motion with graphic screen content.Recorded at INK Asia 2016, Singapore

How do we cooperate with the Indian Government? Madan Padaki explains the different ways stakeholders can interact with each other to efficiently engage with our country’s systems and more importantly, find the right people within to work with.

Pallavi Gupta narrates how she went about not just bridging the gap between government officers, NGO’s and corporates - by bringing them together to understand specific social issues many regions in India face - but also implement innovative solutions.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Chandan Gomes takes us through his journey in search of a young girl whose drawing book he found abandoned in a hospice in Jaipur and whose mountain drawings he went on to emulate in photographs as a tribute to her longing for the mountains.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Ecologist, Shannon takes the audience through the biodiversity of the nature around us and how, all life, from the smallest bacteria to the largest elephant, uses unique chemicals to communicate with each other and with their environment.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

column2: Which city would you like to see dance?
column8: Architectural choreographer Laura Kriefman talks about how she makes cities dance through the medium of mechanical cranes to illustrate how the infrastructure of our cities have an inherent movement and beauty to it.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

Listen to Ezetap's Abhijit Bose expand the world of disruption in Fintech - he talks about different models of how the cloud has encouraged a more interconnected financial system.Recorded at INK2016, Goa
Veerappan Swaminathan tells us about how he uses the 'maker movement' to get communities in Singapore engaged in enjoyable practices that contribute to sustainable living.Recorded at INK2016, Goa

column2: What you lack, will make you run
column8: YourStory’s Shradha Sharma gives a witty take on the typical entrepreneur-investor story; the ruthless world of start-ups in present-day India and encourages us to love what we lack in our lives.Recorded at INK Live 2016, Goa
